<table border=0 cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0><tr><td>
	     <table class=mform  border=0 cellpadding=1 cellspacing=0 width=100%>
	     <form action=/cgi-bin/mrate.pl name=f99718049635473>
	     <tr><td id=headerrow colspan=2 class=mform valign=top><a name=classes2.html?class=12&mid=99718049635473>&nbsp;</a><a id=sj href=classes2.html?class=12&mid=99718049635473>RE: Difficult?</a> <a id=fs8 href=classes2.html?class=12&mid=99718049635473#post><img src=http://everquest.allakhazam.com/static/reply.gif border=0 alt="Reply..." height=16 width=16></a>
	     <br clear=all><small>Posted @ Tue, Aug 7th 6:34 AM 2001</small></td></tr>
	     <tr><td valign=top id=fs8 class=mform><span id=notbold>By:</span> <a href=poster.html?user=21128><span id=Scholar>Beetlebrow</span></a><br><b><span id=Scholar>Scholar</span></b><br><span id=notbold>53 posts<br><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Decent [3.07]</td><td valign=top class=mform width=100%><p>Kadthar here rather than Beetlebrow,<br>(Beetlebrow's only knowkedge of the "difficulty" of Magicians is how stringy they are and how the bones get caught in his throat.)<br><br>OK first of all, I am going to assume that your message is on the up-and-up and not just a veiled slam on mages and rangers as some might guess.&nbsp;&nbsp;:o)<br>Mages are not without difficulty to play.  Their soloing is a good deal more work than the soloing that some other classes do. (Mainly here I mean necros, druids, shamans and perhaps bards, who all have special tactics to use when soloing.) With mages soloing is painfully straightforward .... you send in your pet fully healed and buffed and nuke as much as you need to ... the difficulties come from the lack of any real defense when a monster decides that the pet isn't feats enough.  Mages cannot feign death to get a monster off them as a necro would and usually is not fast enough to run away like other classes, so if the pet cannot regain control of the monster and give you breathing room, you will be toast.  This usually makes it almost required to used the earth pet when soloing as their root lands fairly often at lower levels (more often if you cast Malise) and so you can usually sit back and nuke without fear.  Mages have a few other benefits when soloing....using bandages if you are hurt and not killed can reduce downtime somewhat, but mostly soloing with magicians can be very tricky.<br>Your other consideration that magicians are not so welcome in groups, is a prejudice that sometimes holds, but not as often as one might think especially below level 50.  With their direct damage and their pets they have long been the biggest damage dealers below level 50 (though this may have changed now I think it is still true).  If a mage has trouble getting into a group, it is often due to a misconception of the usefulness of a mage by players who have read some misleading posts. ;o)  Magicians shine in groups dealing great damage for very little mana...I usually only nuke each monster one time and Malise once and then meditate, unless the monster gives the group a rough time in which case I will nuke more.  Because of this after I recover from the initial summoning of my pet I can hold a good mana reserve or at least some mana reserve depending on the speed of the pulling for use in emergencies.  Once people have grouped with magicians who are skilled at their craft they will have no problem joining up with one again.  In a group magicians very rarely will use the earth pet as groups generally have a better way to hold the monster in place than root, and other pets deal better damage.  If it is absolutely essential that a moster stay in place you still might use the earth pet in a group though.<br>One possibility is that you mistake difficulty for finding a group with groups not looking for new members .... often a group will not be full and will not actively pursue new members who shout or use OOC, but if you approach them they will be more than happy to let you join.  Casters especially have little trouble doing this as they can roam invisible in many places looking for groups working with an open spot.<br>Another thing that magicians are particularly good at that your message didn't mention, is neither a full group nor soloing but a partnership.  Especially with one or two people who can harmony or mesmerize or something to single pull creatures, as mages tend to be very effective against single creatures.  A particularly good partner is (you guessed it!) a ranger who has, at some level, most of the things a mage lacks .... with Harmony he can single pull, he has snare, he has some buffs (notably foot speed buffs) and he can track.  Of course druids have all this as well, but rangers serve the additional benefit of giving added melee assistance to a magician.<br>I apologize that this message was so long .... I never really addressed the difficulty of playing a magician per se, but I hope from my descriptions you can maybe gather if it is what you want.  I hope that you find this useful.  These are my observations from research of my own and playing (the pre level 50 game).  The game post level 50 changes considerably and my description here shouldn't be interpreted as describing the later game at all.<br>Have fun and may Quellious watch over you.<br><br>Kadthar Al'Kreshid &lt;Midnight Unity&gt;<br>Level 34 Erudite Gatecaller (Magician)<br>Tholuxe Paells</p>&nbsp;<br></td></tr>
